WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.335 --> 00:00:10.548
Roughly 50% of people will break a bone
at some point in their lives.

00:00:10.715 --> 00:00:13.885
But whether the cause is as mundane
as a slip on the ice

00:00:13.968 --> 00:00:17.221
or as dramatic as a
tightrope-walking accident,

00:00:17.221 --> 00:00:19.807
broken bones tend to heal the same way.

00:00:20.349 --> 00:00:25.271
The human body's 200 plus bones
come in many shapes and sizes,

00:00:25.313 --> 00:00:31.027
referred to by medical professionals
as short bones, long bones, flat bones,

00:00:31.069 --> 00:00:34.530
and the catch-all category
of irregular bones.

00:00:34.989 --> 00:00:36.282
Despite their differences,

00:00:36.282 --> 00:00:40.745
bones generally have a rigid structure
composed of a protein matrix

00:00:40.745 --> 00:00:42.288
that’s dotted with bone cells

00:00:42.288 --> 00:00:45.249
and reinforced with minerals
containing calcium.

00:00:45.333 --> 00:00:49.087
Inside these stiff exteriors
is spongy marrow,

00:00:49.087 --> 00:00:51.964
containing stem cells that can divide
and differentiate

00:00:51.964 --> 00:00:54.008
into specialized cell types.

00:00:54.342 --> 00:00:57.512
Bones are also penetrated
by blood vessels and nerves,

00:00:57.512 --> 00:01:01.474
which relay the searing pain
signal associated with the break.

00:01:01.974 --> 00:01:06.354
Since these nerves are encased in hard
tissue they’re very difficult to study,

00:01:06.562 --> 00:01:10.900
so we still don't know exactly
why broken bones hurt so much.

00:01:11.067 --> 00:01:14.195
But we do know that long bones
are the most likely to break

00:01:14.195 --> 00:01:17.073
since they often take the brunt
of the impact from a fall.

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:20.743
Whether an accident causes a clean break
or a splintering crack,

00:01:20.952 --> 00:01:24.705
any kind of fracture makes the
blood vessels inside the bone rupture,

00:01:24.914 --> 00:01:27.500
causing internal bleeding
and inflammation.

00:01:27.834 --> 00:01:31.754
This signals the body to start the
first step of the healing process:

00:01:31.754 --> 00:01:33.339
the inflammatory phase.

00:01:33.881 --> 00:01:37.510
For the next week, the body floods
the injury site with immune cells

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:39.095
which remove damaged tissue

00:01:39.095 --> 00:01:42.431
and help prepare the site
for healthy new tissue to grow.

00:01:42.765 --> 00:01:47.145
The cells also release signaling molecules
that recruit stem cells to the area.

00:01:47.395 --> 00:01:51.274
As they arrive, these stem cells
differentiate into chondrocytes.

00:01:51.399 --> 00:01:53.943
These cells use the clotted blood
at the break site

00:01:53.943 --> 00:01:57.155
as a scaffold to build callus
made of cartilage.

00:01:57.488 --> 00:02:01.659
Cartilage can grow very quickly,
making it a useful temporary patch.

00:02:01.784 --> 00:02:04.871
But it’s much weaker than bone,
so over the following weeks,

00:02:04.871 --> 00:02:07.123
some of the chondrocytes
and stem cells develop

00:02:07.123 --> 00:02:10.877
into special bone-building cells
called osteoblasts

00:02:10.877 --> 00:02:13.504
that can create a stronger bony callus.

00:02:13.796 --> 00:02:17.592
Once the bony callus is complete,
the remodeling phase can begin.

00:02:18.134 --> 00:02:19.552
Over the next few months,

00:02:19.594 --> 00:02:22.555
another type of cell eats away
at the bony callus

00:02:22.638 --> 00:02:25.308
as osteoblasts lay down new bone tissue.

00:02:25.516 --> 00:02:28.186
This phase is where most
of the bone healing happens,

00:02:28.186 --> 00:02:30.897
restoring the injury site
to its previous shape.

00:02:31.439 --> 00:02:35.484
But the healing timeline varies
widely depending on a patient's diet,

00:02:35.484 --> 00:02:38.571
how much rest they’re getting,
and how messy the break is.

00:02:38.905 --> 00:02:41.115
A clean break generally heals the fastest,

00:02:41.115 --> 00:02:45.203
and doctors use casts and splints
to keep bones aligned as they heal.

00:02:45.494 --> 00:02:48.080
But if the bone has been splintered
into tiny fragments

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:49.749
and significantly displaced,

00:02:49.749 --> 00:02:53.211
surgery may be required
to put those pieces back in place.

00:02:53.544 --> 00:02:56.088
And if a bone does heal while misaligned,

00:02:56.088 --> 00:02:59.091
a surgeon would need to refracture it,
realign it,

00:02:59.091 --> 00:03:03.137
and then use pins, plates, or screws
to hold the bone together.

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:05.514
When the remodelling phase is over,

00:03:05.514 --> 00:03:07.767
there may be a slight bump
at the fracture site,

00:03:07.767 --> 00:03:10.019
but this typically resolves over time,

00:03:10.019 --> 00:03:13.022
leaving the bone just
as strong as it was before.

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:17.526
Naturally, the strength of our bones
varies from person to person.

00:03:17.526 --> 00:03:21.197
And older populations are more likely
to break their bones in the first place,

00:03:21.239 --> 00:03:24.325
since bone density tends
to decrease with age.

00:03:24.617 --> 00:03:27.119
Researchers are still
investigating why this happens,

00:03:27.119 --> 00:03:30.790
but fortunately, we already know
the best way to keep bones strong.

00:03:30.998 --> 00:03:34.585
Even when they aren’t healing,
bones are constantly remodeling—

00:03:34.627 --> 00:03:36.504
adjusting their density and strength

00:03:36.504 --> 00:03:38.714
to the amount of force
they’re typically under.

00:03:38.798 --> 00:03:41.801
So exercises like walking, running,
and weightlifting

00:03:41.801 --> 00:03:44.262
all stimulate your bones
to grow denser.

00:03:44.595 --> 00:03:47.974
Just make sure whatever activity
you're doing is relatively safe,

00:03:47.974 --> 00:03:51.435
because there’s nothing humorous
about a broken humerus.

